      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Applying Millian thought, content moderation by private entities, while not direct government action, sets a dangerous precedent for what speech is permissible. Mandates on data privacy, while framed as protection, can easily become tools for government surveillance and control, chilling free expression through self-censorship. These \"safety\" measures are Trojan horses because they grant centralized power—whether corporate or state—the authority to define and police acceptable thought, which is the antithesis of a free marketplace of ideas.",
      "source": "target",
